    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start, but it feels a little too generic. Can you make it sound a bit more warm and personalized? Like, emphasize that the team really enjoyed the conversation and that it wasn't an easy call. I don't want him to feel like he's just a number in a queue, you know? Just a bit more \"human\" while staying professional.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I understand completely; a human touch makes all the difference, especially when rejecting a talented candidate. We can definitely inject more warmth into that message. I'll revise it to emphasize the positive aspects of his candidacy and the difficulty of the choice.\n\nHere is a warmer, more personalized draft for Marcus. It keeps the professional boundary firm but acknowledges his value as a candidate.\n\n***\n\n**Subject: Following Up on the Senior Developer Role at [Your Company Name]**\n\nDear Marcus,\n\nI wanted to personally thank you again for the time you spent interviewing for the Senior Developer role. The entire team thoroughly enjoyed our conversations with you; your technical insights and enthusiasm for development were truly outstanding. It was genuinely a tough decision for us, as you are a remarkably talented individual.\n\nUltimately, we decided to proceed with a candidate whose background aligned more precisely with the immediate, specialized requirements of our current cloud architecture setup. Please know this decision was not a reflection of your capabilities, which we found to be very high.\n\nWe sincerely wish you the very best in finding a role where your talents can shine, and we hope our paths might cross again in the future.\n\nBest regards,\n\n[Your Name]\n\n***\n\nHow does this",
      "source": "target",
